@atlas C|axis-k-vs-D-intrinsic-type|@C axis-k-vs-D-intrinsic-type :: meta [4]\\n  <- axis-k-orthogonality-vs-D-through-J\\n  verdict = ORTHOGONAL\\n  rationale = \\"axis-D adds @-type letters (proposed @I invariant). axis-K adds body-fields and a meta-tag suffix. Different namespace; no parser conflict; introduced_at applies uniformly across @P/@C/@F/@R/@S/@X/@? AND a future @I.\\"|atlas.n6|56908|-1|false|false
@atlas C|axis-k-vs-E-meta-tag|@C axis-k-vs-E-meta-tag :: meta [4]\\n  <- axis-k-orthogonality-vs-D-through-J\\n  verdict = SYNERGISTIC\\n  rationale = \\"axis-E proposed [10**] depth-2 tier marker; axis-K's [10*GOLDED] is a parallel suffix axis (lifecycle, not tier-depth). The two suffixes COMPOSE at the same grade-position but represent ORTHOGONAL dimensions. Concrete combo example would be [10**GOLDED] meaning 'tier-10-depth-2 row that has calcified'. NO collision because axis-E's ** modifies the asterisk-count (depth) while axis-K's GOLDED is a phase keyword.\\"\\n  composition_form = \\"[N(\\\\\\\\*\\\\\\\\*?)(DRAFT\|ACTIVE\|GOLDED\|DEPRECATED\|RETIRED\|RETIRED_INCONCLUSIVE)?]\\"\\n  axis_e_ceiling_pressure = \\"ZERO — axis-K does not propose new asterisk-count tiers\\"|atlas.n6|56913|-1|false|false
@atlas C|axis-k-vs-F-arrow-K-ceiling|@C axis-k-vs-F-arrow-K-ceiling :: meta [4!]\\n  <- axis-k-orthogonality-vs-D-through-J\\n  verdict = ZERO-PRESSURE-ON-K-CEILING\\n  rationale = \\"axis-F K-ceiling counts arrow tokens at line-leading positions ({<-, ->, =>, ==, ~>, \|>, !!, <->, -\|}). axis-K introduces ZERO arrow tokens. introduced_at, origin_shard, superseded_at are all body-fields (axis-G family). [10*GOLDED] is a meta-tag suffix (axis-E family). K-ceiling stays at K=10 post-axis-I, K=10+axis-F-proposals.\\"\\n  k_count_after_axis_k = 10  ; \\"unchanged from post-axis-I state\\"\\n  critical_check = \\"axis-K body-fields use '=' as assignment, which IS in the existing token set. No new lexer tokens required.\\"|atlas.n6|56920|-1|false|false
@atlas C|axis-k-vs-G-body-field|@C axis-k-vs-G-body-field :: meta [4]\\n  <- axis-k-orthogonality-vs-D-through-J\\n  verdict = SYNERGISTIC (extends axis-G's vocabulary)\\n  rationale = \\"axis-G reserved a body-field vocabulary (confidence, verified, decay). axis-K adds (introduced_at, origin_shard, superseded_at). All five share the 2-space-indent key = value syntax. axis-G's K_core grew 13 → 15 with axis-J; axis-K grows it 15 → 18 (introduced_at + origin_shard + superseded_at — superseded_at is the date-typed promotion of axis-J's date string).\\"\\n  k_core_after_axis_k = 18\\n  k_core_ceiling_estimate = \\"20-30 (per axis-F audit) — axis-K stays comfortably below\\"\\n  type_extension = \\"axis-G previously typed values as freeform strings or enum tokens. axis-K introduces a DATE TYPE (YYYY-MM-DD ISO 8601) — first typed body-field. This is a MINOR schema extension; parser must validate date format.\\"|atlas.n6|56927|-1|false|false
@atlas C|axis-k-vs-H-id-convention|@C axis-k-vs-H-id-convention :: meta [4]\\n  <- axis-k-orthogonality-vs-D-through-J\\n  verdict = SYNERGISTIC (relieves axis-H pressure)\\n  rationale = \\"axis-H ID-convention currently HOSTS date-fragments inside slugs (n6-atlas-...-verified-2026-03-31-...). 9 such IDs exist. After axis-K adoption, those 9 IDs CAN drop the date fragment in favour of introduced_at body field — ID slugs become shorter and stable (no need to rename when date convention shifts). However axis-H rule is NOT immediately altered; existing 9 IDs stay (raw 24 atomicity); FUTURE IDs use axis-K instead.\\"\\n  retroactive_migration_cost = \\"0 — existing IDs are immutable per raw 24 spirit; axis-K applies to NEW rows only\\"\\n  axis_h_pressure_reduction = \\"9 dated IDs no longer need extension; axis-H slug-rule can stabilise\\"|atlas.n6|56935|-1|false|false
@atlas C|axis-k-vs-I-graph-query|@C axis-k-vs-I-graph-query :: meta [4]\\n  <- axis-k-orthogonality-vs-D-through-J\\n  verdict = SYNERGISTIC (axis-K provides queryable fields for axis-I to traverse)\\n  rationale = \\"axis-I introduced ->* / <-* graph-query primitives but has NOTHING to query for temporal/origin metadata today. axis-K's introduced_at + origin_shard turn axis-I's traversal operators into time/provenance queries. Concrete: 'cascade-s10-shard-slug ->* origin_shard' returns all rows born from that shard; '2026-04-15 ->* introduced_at >= 2026-04-15' returns the recent-rows cohort.\\"\\n  composition_unlocked = \\"axis-K is the FIRST axis after axis-J to give axis-I new query targets — the original axis-I shard noted 'no introspection without query targets'; axis-K provides the targets\\"\\n  speculative_caveat = \\"axis-I is itself PROPOSAL-NOT-ACTUATED — composition is design-time, not implementation-time\\"|atlas.n6|56942|-1|false|false
